Russia and Turkey: An alliance of the “incompatible”?
It was a gesture that ended in crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce a formal end to the eight-month-long verbal war and economic sanctions.
But while Vladimir Putin welcomed the Turkish counterparty in the luxury hall of the palace in St. Petersburg, I had the impression that Ankara wanted more for this reconciliation.
There was a handshake, yes.
But Putin didn't smile, and he was barely radiating warmth, even by his measured standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken about his “dear friend” Mr Putin – five times, as reported by one of the reports.
I didn't count it.
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their level before the crisis, but would be even better.
The next day, one of the local newspapers wrote that Erdogan had acted as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I think his enthusiasm revealed the exact opposite.
But the persistent cold that emanated from Putin showed that the Russian leader had forgotten nothing.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: The shooting down of a Russian warplane by Turkey on the Syrian border.
Moscow's reaction back then was furious.
Putin dealt wounds around him and accused Ankara of putting a knife in Moscow's back.
The scandal was all the greater because it came from a supposed friend.
Rebuilding true trust will be difficult, perhaps even impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
State-controlled media have waged a massive nationwide campaign against Ankara for months.
Suddenly it looked like the Turks were to blame for everything.
More serious were the allegations from top state officials that Erdogan's own family benefited from illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He strongly denied this.
But in St. Petersburg came the official message that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting came only because Putin received the apology he demanded of President Erdogan.
Russia could also declare victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of declaring a ceasefire are clear.
In the first place, Erdogan was almost deprived of power last month during a failed coup and therefore needs all his friends.
Repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have also visibly rocked him.
There is also an economic motive.
Russian sanctions have had a harsh impact - primarily the cancellation of charter flights, which carry several million Russian tourists on the coast of Turkey every year.
That number decreased by almost 90%.
As for Russia, tour operators and charter companies will surely relax when flights are restored.
They earn on Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television promised cheaper fruits and vegetables when imports of agricultural commodities from Turkey were allowed again.
“Tourists there, tomatoes back here,” as the news in the Vedemosti newspaper proclaimed.
But the visit had another political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West for what he considers a feeble reaction to the coup attempt.
In addition, long-standing animosity lengthy talks on joining the EU and Putin's entry - which is eager to allow the cooling to take advantage of and break Turkey's bonds with the West.
The Russian leader certainly earned bonus points when Ankara asked him for the help of elected authorities after attempting a coup.
You have to understand that for Moscow, which has a deep-rooted fear of regime change, it is a given.
So the summit in this pompous, seaside palace to Russia and Turkey has allowed me to demonstrate what one of the analysts described to me as a “companion of the incompatible”: how the forces of the two countries that feel rejected and exploited by the West are joining forces.
However, despite the fact that they have publicly shown reconciliation, there are fundamental differences between the two countries.
The first is Syria, where Moscow recently took on the role of a peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey stand on opposite sides.
It could be said that after nearly three hours of opening talks, the two presidents said at a press conference that they had not even mentioned the issue.
Turkey's president deliberately challenged the answer to a question about the differences between them, while Putin decided to highlight those differences.
There is no clear agreement on the basis of which the two states can find common ground on the issue of Syria.
But after months of open hostility - and given the risk of utter disaster when a NATO member Turkey shot down a Russian warplane - it is certainly better that the two leaders at least talk to each other again.
