Court in France refuses to demolish shops in Jungle refugee camp
A court in France has dismissed an order by authorities in Calais to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, where thousands of refugees live.
During a court hearing this week, authorities in Calais argued that the state should be allowed to cancel a total of 72 makeshift shops where people inside the camp sell goods, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer haircuts, in makeshift restaurants selling tea for 50 cents or basic dishes for several euros.
The Prefect's office in Calais argued that places need to be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they pose a danger of fire and health risks.
Humanitarian organizations have said in court that shops and restaurants are vital and that free meals offered by state-backed associations and other groups do not provide a food supplement for the growing number of refugees in the camp.
Disputed makeshift shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to people in need.
The court in Lille ruled that there was no legal basis to prevent people from running 72 makeshift deals, but said the objections of Prefect Calais were "completely understandable."
Judge Jean-François Molla said grocery stores, cafes and restaurants have a far greater role than simply serving food to people who "live in extraordinarily desperate conditions."
He said the premises provide quiet places to meet refugees and volunteers.
One of the places threatened with demolition was the camp cafe, the Jungle Book Kids, which is run by a non-profit organization that offers 200 meals, English and French classes a day, and asylum counseling for hundreds of unaccompanied minors at the camp.
The petition for the protection of the “children’s” cafe was signed by more than 170 000 people.
The Guardian received a letter saying that the closure of the café “was a disaster for these children, some of them are only 8 years old.”
On Friday, the charity Help Refugess and L'Auberge des Migrants estimated that the number of refugees in the camp after a steep increase in arrivals during the summer has risen to more than 9,000 - which is the most in all times.
