We would recommend cooperation with the architect to anyone, if he designs an apartment from the beginning, because it is a very complex technical process.
The second level is the interior design itself: designers have a significantly better idea of a range of possible materials and, based on the client’s wishes, are able to match the interior appropriately.
We cooperated with the architect Lenka Langerová on our mountain apartment, then on the basis of a personal recommendation of another client, and since everything worked well, it was an obvious choice for us even during the reconstruction of our new apartment in Vinohrady.
What were your practical and aesthetic requirements?
We wanted a generous social-living space with adequate facilities for a family of four conceived as a modern, but not a cold interior.
The priority was to achieve the connection of the apartment with terraces and to implement intelligent control of the household.
And, of course, it was necessary to monitor the quality of the implementation.
Did you leave everything to the experts, or did you interfere with the final form of the interior yourself?
All designs, including technical drawings and samples of materials, were approved, but the design was always from architects.
At the beginning, we determined what we expected from the design, and showed some elements of the interior that we would like to incorporate into the design, for example, carpets or paintings.
I think that our collection of mostly Czech authors, including works by Karel Malich, Karel Vysušil, Václav Špála or Otto Gutfreund, helped the architect to navigate our taste.
Also, the combination of black, white and walnut wood was the architect's idea as well as individual pieces of furniture, walls, floor, lighting, carpets, textiles, art, etc. Whether everything is tuned together, we then verified together through visualizations.
Did any complications appear during the realization, because of which you had to give up the original ideas, or, on the contrary, to accept new ones?
Perhaps only in the initial phase of the project, when we came to the construction at the moment when it was first possible to climb to the height of our floor, and found that the views we were planning actually shaded the surrounding buildings.
Back then, we literally changed the layout overnight from the ground up.
Granite was used on the kitchen counter and on the lining of the fireplace wall.
The interior is dominated by wooden surfaces complemented by leather, for example, on the upholstery of the dining and bar chairs of the Norma from Arper.
How would you characterize the interior?
Are you planning any changes or is there something you would like to have differently today?
I believe that it is a modern airy interior, which primarily fulfills its purpose.
We are not planning changes, most of the modifications after moving in took place in the level of shielding and housing terraces.
Perhaps the only complaint is to the floor, when walnut wood turns out to be too delicate for a household with a dog.
The Word of the Architects, Ing. arch. Lenka Langerová and MgA. Kamila Hornychová, author of the realization.
The apartment is on the last floor of the new building, so it was possible to make a completely new layout and several other modifications within the construction.
For the interior, an important element is the placement of the light pipes in the ceiling of the hallway and the main toilet.
This puts the daylight in the darker areas of the apartment.
Also, the direct access from the main bathroom to the roof terrace to the pool from the USSPA is one of the building modifications, which was very beneficial for the function of the whole apartment.
There is also a swimming pool and a hot tub.
Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim woman living in Prague.
You come from France.
Where did you live before you moved to Prague?
My parents are originally from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, just outside the Spanish border.
I've been moving quite a bit.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
I studied journalism in France, which made me want to work in a magazine.
Why did you decide to move out of the country?
I was beginning to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere among people.
I thought every Frenchman was very negative.
People in France are negatively attuned in general, but it's gotten worse lately.
Interestingly, you mention negativity.
Some people evaluate the Czech nature in this way.
Believe me, compared to the French, you are not negative.
It may not seem like that to some people when they come to France, because they don't see it as tourists.
But it was too much for me.
The big issue is money.
People feel that they have little money, while the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which I think is enough.
Now there is a problem with people's behavior towards Muslims.
That's completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street I lived in, my non-Muslim neighbor started looking at me through his fingers just because I was Muslim.
Like I'm some kind of evil.
That's why I didn't feel well in France.
But my family stayed there.
So you've decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job basically anywhere else and I came across a vacancy at Air France here in Prague.
I have to admit that I did not know Prague at the beginning.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I didn’t know what to expect from Prague.
I've been here three years now and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Mainly because of a completely different atmosphere.
Maybe it's because I don't speak Czech, so I can't catch some negative reactions or swearing, but I feel like people here are freer.
That I can do anything, dress in any way, and no one will judge me.
In France, someone is always looking at you unpleasantly, for example, when you have special clothes and the like.
I started to feel really free in Prague.
I don't think Praguers care about such things.
Where do you work now?
After working at Air France, I worked for a travel website for a while.
Then we started a website with another friend on which people offer and look for shared housing.
So far we are only operating in Prague, but we would like to extend it to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends who are Czechs halfway, and two more friends of the Czechs.
I have to say that another specificity of the Czechs is that at first they keep their distance more.
He won't let someone near his body.
That's quite different from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses on the cheek.
It's different here, but I understand it's a cultural issue, so I'm trying to adapt.
You mentioned that you don't speak Czech.
Is language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, it is quite simple in Prague, because perhaps everyone here speaks English.
Even in curfews or in food.
I want to learn Czech, but I don’t have that much time.
And by being able to communicate at least a little in English, I don’t have that need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there's someone who can help me.
Have you encountered any negative reactions?
Maybe because you're Muslim?
Basically, no.
Perhaps it is also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My manager, a Czech, once told me about the French football team and said something in the sense of: They are not French, but Africans.
That touched me quite a bit.
But that someone would have a problem with being a Muslim has not happened to me yet.
This is despite the fact that a colleague once warned me of some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He said don't go downtown, they'll swear at me.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly related to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something similar to Paris, Nice or Brussels can happen in Prague?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is that anything can happen anywhere these days.
Until recently, I could not have imagined that such a thing would happen in France.
And it's not just about Muslims.
Islam does not recognize violence.
For me, the people who kill are not Muslims.
The Quran says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel when terrorists shield themselves from your faith?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, although I should not feel that way at all.
I try not to follow the violence reports, but every time I read something, I feel the need to apologize for something that's not really my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for terrorists?
We met at Jiřího z Poděbrady Square.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims, along with Christians, demonstrated against violence.
Did you register it?
I didn't know about that.
But I understand that these people feel the need to prove that they disagree with the violence.
I don't think they have to do anything like that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn't cause?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
My co-workers are from Egypt and other Muslim countries, for example.
They're a little more religious than I am, so sometimes we have quite wild discussions about Islam because we all perceive it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, for example, they learned Islam in school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordinate status of women.
How do you feel about it?
I don't feel subordinate to myself in any way.
Rather the opposite.
I'm a woman, I have the strength.
It also has to do with the fact that you do not wear any headgear.
For example, the hijab?
And it's mostly the way I was raised.
My mother, for example, is a really principled Muslim.
He prays five times a day, but he just doesn't wear the scarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It depends on everyone how they interpret it.
When you read the Quran, you should make up your own mind about those things.
So when I read a passage in the Quran that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself: I am not the Prophet’s wife, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect that, and when I come to Iran or Saudi Arabia, where they require headscarves, I take it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
So far, yes.
I didn't feel so good anywhere else.
I thought about Poland for a while, but I feel great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
I think Prague is the ideal city for this.
