You pick up the packages like Pokémon.
They want to compete with the carriers.
The idea to use the already planned journey for the transport of shipments is the television director Matěj Liška and the manager of the Prague music club Marek Greger.
With the idea, they breathed life into a trio of applications with different geographical reach.
We launched the national application Transfer in May.
At the moment, there are thousands of cities in it and we will expand the network.
In the Czech Republic, we want to learn this before we focus more on foreign countries, says the forty-one-year-old manager in an interview with iDNES.cz.
How does the Transfer app work and who can benefit from it?
You can download it and register for free.
Then you can enter the route and data, how much you can transport the large package and how much you want.
Someone may be in demand for transport on that day.
When the route and the time of delivery are suitable, it is paired and both of them receive mutual notification.
At that moment, the chat opens, where the pair arrange a handover.
How many people do you think would have to register for each package to always find their courier?
I do not know the ideal state, I can not estimate how many registered and how many paths it takes to make the coverage completely optimal and each offer paired with demand.
It already works on the main routes and it is logically easier than, for example, on the road between villages.
The more people, the greater the potential for speed and accuracy.
In the meantime, people are also building up trust and discovering that no one will run away with the package.
Have you not had to deal with such a case yet?
How many users have the service two months after launch?
Currently, we have about 5 to 6 thousand people who create paths.
We consider this a success and we believe that others will be packed.
Isn't there a danger that the sender will wait too long?
We hope to be a competition for big conglomerates just because we are able to deliver the thing the same day and for a fraction of the price.
With a large company, you will pay several thousand for delivery within two hours.
Here you pay maybe a hundred or less, because that's the way someone already does business.
Should traditional carriers be worried about a potential loss of customers in the future?
We hope it will be so.
The market has huge potential, feeding on huge multinational carriers, as well as retail chains, where everyone started shopping and gradually found that the quality does not match what they pay for.
No one wants to find a note in the mailbox with a message that he should pick up the shipment at the branch, first the day after 19 o'clock.
By that time I had needed the package for six hours and I was waiting at home because it was important.
We want a better, faster and functional service that won't annoy anyone and send a signal to the competition, let them try.
Marek Greger (41) and Matěj Liška (39).
