Kepler measures the rotation speed of stars in the Pleiades
The Kepler Space Telescope's latest mission to help astronomers is to obtain an almost complete list of speeds of star rotation from the Pleiades cluster.
New data helps astronomers understand why stars in the cluster spin at different speeds, and also how the rotation time is related to the formation of the planet.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between star mass, its age and even the history of its solar system," Luisa Rebull, a researcher at the Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, said in a new report.
The Pleiades cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now reaching a state of maturity and have formed for about 125 million years.
Now it is turning the fastest.
At moments of maximum rotational speeds, these teenage stars release huge amounts of star wind.
Because these winds move along the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a slowing effect on them.
As the star ages, its rotational speed slows.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by measuring the time between discovering recognizable points on stars ---- similar to sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotational speeds, larger stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, bigger make pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
“In the ‘ballet’ of the Pleiades, we see that slower-spinning stars are more massive, while those that spin the fastest are usually very light stars,” Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory to compare the quality of stars and the speed of rotation.
“The pleiads provide us with an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, in younger and older stars,” Rebull said.
There’s still a lot we want to learn about how, when, and why the stars slow down their rotational speed and so to speak, “hang their dancing shoes on the cloves.”
Rebull and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of the speed of rotation of the Pleiades in three studies, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a Qualification Agreement necessary?
If I didn't apply, then the qualifying agreement would not be concluded and after a few months I could go to another hospital?
Is it even possible to work without applying for specialization education after graduation?
The point is that in the field in which I would like to work, there is now a vacancy only in a somewhat more distant hospital, but in about half a year it could be possible to free up space in another, where I would like to work afterwards.
So I don't know how to deal with the situation about half a year, the question continues.
Answers Mgr. Lenka Vlková.
No legislation stipulates the obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with the employer - the hospital.
The Qualification Agreement is a legal institute governed by the Labour Code and can be concluded between the employee and the employer in order to ensure a return on the costs incurred associated with increasing or deepening the employee’s qualifications.
In the field of health care, there is long-term pressure on the non-constitution of these agreements with a view to ensuring the work mobility of healthcare professionals, and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
According to Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on the conditions for obtaining and recognizing professional competence and specialized competence to pursue the medical profession of a doctor, dentist and pharmacist, it is expressly the case that participation in specialization education is considered to be a deepening of qualifications (not an increase in it).
This means that the qualification agreement can only be concluded under the Labour Code if the costs amount to at least 75 000 Kč.
No legislation even stipulates the obligation to apply for specialization education.
The Act only lays down the conditions for the application for inclusion in the field of specialization education.
However, according to the law, the doctor is entitled to pursue the profession of a doctor already thanks to the completion of the necessary university studies, even if under the statutory conditions (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The law anticipates a situation where professional experience completed in another field of specialization can be included in the specialization education of the doctor, if its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
In theory, it would be possible to count the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the interviewer's situation.
However, in view of the fact that I do not know the circumstances of this case, it is recommended to consult with the relevant Department of the Ministry of Health (Department of Science and Medical Occupations), since the Ministry of Health by law provides a counselling and consultation service related to the inclusion in and course of specialization education.
The advisory service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
Doctors from Syria's Halab are asking for U.S. intervention.
The United States has not made any effort to end the siege (rebel parts of the city by government troops), and has not used its influence to enforce the protection of civilians, the White House said.
"We do not need tears, compassion, and even prayers; however, we desperately need to create a no-fly zone over eastern Halab to stop the attacks, and we need international action to ensure that Halab is not surrounded again," the doctors said.
Russian forces, who support the military loyal to President Bashar al-Assad, have announced that from today, strikes in the Halab area will stop every day for three hours to allow safe passage to humanitarian convoys.
All military activities, air strikes and artillery fire are to be stopped from 9:00 to 12:00 CEST.
While UN humanitarian operations chief Stephen O'Brien welcomed this, he stressed the need for at least a two-day cease-fire.
According to the AFP, 15 of the 35 doctors who operate in the eastern part of Halab, already controlled by the rebels, turned to Obama in the letter.
They write that during the five-year war, they witnessed the violent, cruel deaths of countless patients, friends and colleagues.
The world is watching and noting how complex Syria is, but it does little to protect us.
Recent offers of evacuation of residents from the Syrian regime and Russia sound like only slightly obscured threats, pediatricians, surgeons and other doctors pointed out.
Doctors said there have been 42 attacks on medical facilities in Syria in the past month, including 15 on the hospitals they work in.
We are most sad that we have to decide who will live and who will die.
Young children with such serious injuries come to our emergency room that we have to choose between them those that are most likely to survive.
And sometimes we don't even have the necessary material to help them, doctors described.
Two weeks ago, four newborns suffocated when the blast interrupted oxygen supplies to their incubators.
They gasped, and then their lives were over - before he could really begin, they reminded.
The army loyal to President Bashar al-Assad, backed by Russian forces, has surrounded the rebel-controlled eastern part of Halab in recent weeks, with more than 200,000 people without food supplies inside.
The rebels, who are under constant strikes by the Russian and Syrian air forces, managed to break the encirclement on Saturday after three weeks and launch a counteroffensive.
Both sides were then joined in and around the city.
